## Read Models (Projections)

A projection listens to domain events and builds a read-optimized view. Each query type gets its own optimized model.

```java
@Component
public class OrderSummaryProjection {

    @EventHandler
    public void on(OrderPlacedEvent event) {
        // Build denormalized summary for the list view
        orderSummaryRepo.save(OrderSummaryDocument.builder()
            .orderId(event.getOrderId())
            .customerName(event.getCustomerName()) // denormalized!
            .itemCount(event.getItems().size())
            .totalAmount(event.getTotal())
            .status("PLACED")
            .placedAt(event.getOccurredAt())
            .build());
    }

    @EventHandler
    public void on(OrderShippedEvent event) {
        orderSummaryRepo.updateStatus(event.getOrderId(), "SHIPPED");
        orderSummaryRepo.updateTrackingNumber(event.getOrderId(), event.getTrackingNumber());
    }

    @EventHandler
    public void on(OrderCancelledEvent event) {
        orderSummaryRepo.updateStatus(event.getOrderId(), "CANCELLED");
    }
}
```

## Multiple Specialized Read Models

One domain, many read models — each optimized for its query:

```java
// Query 1: Order list for customer dashboard
// Needs: orderId, date, total, status — fast list
OrderSummaryProjection → PostgreSQL table

// Query 2: Full order details page
// Needs: everything including line items, addresses
OrderDetailProjection → MongoDB document

// Query 3: Analytics dashboard
// Needs: aggregates, time-series
OrderAnalyticsProjection → ClickHouse/TimescaleDB

// Query 4: Search orders by product name
OrderSearchProjection → Elasticsearch index
```

Each can use a completely different data store suited to its query type.

## Handling Eventual Consistency

Read models are eventually consistent — there's a lag between writing and the read model being updated. Strategies for clients:

1. **Optimistic UI** — update UI immediately assuming success, sync later
2. **Return the command result** — return enough data with the 202 response so client doesn't need to re-query immediately
3. **Version tracking** — client polls until read model version >= command version
4. **Event streaming to client** — push projection updates via WebSocket/SSE

```java
// Return enough in the command response
@PostMapping("/orders")
public ResponseEntity<PlaceOrderResponse> placeOrder(...) {
    OrderId id = commandBus.send(command);
    return ResponseEntity.accepted().body(
        PlaceOrderResponse.builder()
            .orderId(id)
            .status("PLACED")          // tell client without needing re-query
            .estimatedTotal(command.getTotal())
            .build()
    );
}
```
